library(ggplot2)
suppressWarnings(suppressMessages(library(ggplot2)))
suppressWarnings(suppressMessages(library(ggthemes)))

# Load the EV dataset
ev_data <- read.csv("F:/data science/r/evechicle_dataset.csv")

# Convert character variables to factors 
ev_data$Year=as.factor(ev_data$Year)
ev_data$Vehicle_Type=as.factor(ev_data$Vehicle_Type)

# Initial ggplot for EV Sales Quantity
n = nrow(ev_data)
rowind = seq(1, n)

# Layer 1: Setting the 2D space for plotting
ggplot(ev_data, aes(x=rowind, y=EV_Sales_Quantity))

# Layer 2: Choosing a geometry to plot
ggplot(ev_data, aes(x=rowind, y=EV_Sales_Quantity)) +
    geom_point(size=2, color="skyblue")

EV_plot1 = ggplot(ev_data, 
                          aes(x=rowind,y=EV_Sales_Quantity)) + 
  geom_point(shape=23,size=1.75,col="pink")

EV_plot1

# Layer 3: Adding labels and titles
EV_plot2=EV_plot1+
          labs(title="Electric Vehicle Sales Quantity", 
          subtitle="From EV Dataset", 
          x="Data Series Number", 
          y="Sales Quantity", 
          caption="EV Data") +
          theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5, size=16, face="bold"),
          plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust=0.5, size=12, face="italic"))
EV_plot2

# Layer 4: Boxplot for EV Sales Quantity
ggplot(ev_data, aes(y=EV_Sales_Quantity)) + 
  geom_boxplot(color="red", fill="yellow") +
  labs(title="Boxplot of EV Sales Quantity", y="Sales Quantity", x="")

# Pie Chart for Vehicle Classes
ggplot(ev_data, aes(x = "", fill = Vehicle_Class)) +
  geom_bar() +
  coord_polar(theta = "y") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Electric Vehicle Classes") +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

# Donut Plot for Vehicle Classes
ggplot(ev_data, aes(x = 2, fill = Vehicle_Class)) +
  geom_bar() +
  coord_polar(theta = "y") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Electric Vehicle Classes") +
  xlim(0, 2.5) +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

# Scatter Plot: EV_Sales_Quantity vs Year
ggplot(ev_data, aes(x = Year, y = EV_Sales_Quantity)) +
  geom_point(color = "maroon", alpha = 0.6) +
  labs(title = "EV Sales vs Year",
       x = "Year", y = "Sales Quantity") +
  theme_minimal()

# Scatter Plot: EV_Sales_Quantity vs Year with Vehicle Class as color
ggplot(ev_data, aes(x = Year, y = EV_Sales_Quantity, color = Vehicle_Class)) +
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +
  labs(title = "Sales Quantity vs Year (Colored by Vehicle Class)",
       x = "Year", y = "Sales Quantity") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

# Boxplot: EV Sales Quantity by State
ggplot(ev_data, aes(x = State, y = EV_Sales_Quantity, fill = State)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of EV Sales by State",
       x = "State", y = "Sales Quantity") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

# Select only numeric variables for correlation analysis
numeric_vars = student_data[, sapply(student_data, is.numeric)]

# Compute the correlation matrix
cor_matrix = round(cor(numeric_vars, use = "complete.obs"), 3)

# Basic correlation plot
corrplot(cor_matrix)

# Enhanced correlation plot with adjustments
corrplot(
  cor_matrix,
  method = "number",             # Show correlation coefficients
  type = "lower",                # Show only lower triangle
  number.digits = 2,            # Display 2 digits for correlation coefficients
  cl.lim = c(-1, 1),             # Limits for the color scale
  col = colorRampPalette(c("darkblue", "red", "darkgreen"))(10),  # Color palette
  tl.pos = "n"                   
)
## Warning in title(title, ...): "cl.lim" is not a graphical parameter

        columns=c("Hours_Studied", "Attendance", "Parental_Involvement", 
                  "Access_to_Resources", "Exam_Score"),
        title = "Student performance Correlations",  
        axisLabels = "none")

#Basic density plot for Exam_Score
ggplot(student_data, aes(x = Exam_Score)) +
  geom_density(fill = "skyblue", alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Density Plot of Exam Scores", 
       x = "Exam Score", 
       y = "Density") +
  theme_minimal()

# Density plot grouped by Gender
ggplot(student_data, aes(x = Exam_Score, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Density Plot of Exam Scores by Gender", 
       x = "Exam Score", 
       y = "Density") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.title = element_blank())

# Density plot grouped by School_Type
ggplot(student_data, aes(x = Exam_Score, fill = School_Type)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Density Plot of Exam Scores by School Type", 
       x = "Exam Score", 
       y = "Density") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.title = element_blank())

# Stacked bar plot: Gender distribution by School_Type
ggplot(student_data, aes(x = School_Type, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Gender by School Type", 
       x = "School Type", 
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.title = element_blank())

# Stacked bar plot with percentage
ggplot(student_data, aes(x = School_Type, fill = Parental_Education_Level)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  labs(title = "Proportion of Parental Education Level by School Type", 
       x = "School Type", 
       y = "Proportion") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.title = element_blank())

# Grouped bar plot: Gender distribution by School_Type
ggplot(student_data, aes(x = School_Type, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Gender Distribution by School Type", 
       x = "School Type", 
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.title = element_blank())

# Custom stacked bar plot with user-defined colors
ggplot(student_data, aes(x = School_Type, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_bar() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("skyblue", "pink")) +
  labs(title = "Customized Stacked Bar Plot", 
       x = "School Type", 
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.title = element_blank())

# Scatter plot for sleephours and exam score
ggplot(student_data, aes(x = Sleep_Hours, y = Exam_Score, color = Motivation_Level)) + 
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.6) + 
  labs(title = "Exam Score vs Sleep Hours by Motivation Level", 
       x = "Sleep Hours", y = "Exam Score") + 
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

#facet grid Internet Access and Tutoring Sessions vs Exam Score

  theme_minimal()

#default scaling

PL1 <- ggplot(student_data, aes(x = Hours_Studied, y = Exam_Score, color = Parental_Involvement)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  xlab("Hours Studied") + 
  ylab("Exam Score") + 
  facet_grid(Access_to_Resources ~ Extracurricular_Activities) + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("pink", "black", "brown", "green"))

PL2 <- ggplot(student_data, aes(x = Hours_Studied, y = Exam_Score, color = Parental_Involvement)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  xlab("Hours Studied") + 
  ylab("Exam Score") + 
  facet_grid(Access_to_Resources ~ Extracurricular_Activities, scales = "free") + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("pink", "black", "brown", "green"))

# Compare
gridExtra::grid.arrange(PL1, PL2, ncol = 2)

#free scaling 
# Without any condition on space
PL3 <- ggplot(student_data, aes(x = Hours_Studied, y = Exam_Score, color = Parental_Involvement)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  xlab("Hours Studied") + 
  ylab("Exam Score") + 
  facet_grid(Access_to_Resources ~ Extracurricular_Activities, scales = "free") + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("blue", "pink", "yellow", "green"))

# Space - equal
PL4 <- ggplot(student_data, aes(x = Hours_Studied, y = Exam_Score, color = Parental_Involvement)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  xlab("Hours Studied") + 
  ylab("Exam Score") + 
  facet_grid(Access_to_Resources ~ Extracurricular_Activities, scales = "free", space = "free") + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
  scale_color_manual(values = c("blue", "pink", "yellow", "green"))

# Compare
gridExtra::grid.arrange(PL3, PL4, ncol = 2)
